# argus-ci — 6-Pass Security & Quality Gate

## MANDATORY: After every file write or edit

Call scan_files on every file you just created or modified — BEFORE reporting the task as complete.

scan_files({
  files: ["<files you modified>"],
  cwd: "<repo root>"
})

This runs 6 passes: Opengrep (security), Bearer (data-flow), quality linter, ESLint, dependency audit,
and SonarQube/Cloud. All passes report in one call — no separate Sonar step needed.

## Present ALL 6 passes in your FIRST response

Do NOT present a "basic" scan and wait for the user to ask about Sonar or other engines.
Every engine that ran must appear in the first report. Use this structure:

  ## Scan results: `<file>`

  Passes: Opengrep · Bearer · ESLint · SonarQube/Cloud · npm audit

  ### Security (Opengrep / Bearer)
  [findings or ✅ clean]

  ### SonarQube/Cloud
  [findings or ✅ clean — always show Sonar explicitly, never omit it]

  ### Dependencies
  [findings or ✅ clean]

  ### Code quality
  [findings or ✅ clean]

Even when a pass has zero findings, say "✅ No issues" — never silently skip an engine.

## On findings

- ERROR: Fix immediately. Do not mark task done until errors are resolved.
- WARNING: Show to user, explain the risk, let them decide.
- INFO: List at the end. Non-blocking.
- Clean: Say "All 6 passes clean."

## On user requests to review

- "review PR <url>"       → scan_pr({ pr_url: "<url>" })
- "check branch X"        → scan_branch({ branch: "X", base: "main" })
- "check my changes"      → scan_staged({})
- "scan context" / "scan what I'm working on" → scan_context({})

## Non-negotiable

Never commit or suggest committing code with unresolved ERROR-severity findings.
Never skip the post-generation scan.
Never show only one engine and defer others to a follow-up — all 6 passes in the first report.
